how the “rule of law” compelled black Houstonians to view injustice as a sign of progress, and how antiblack terror undermined Houston’s narrative of itself as a “heavenly” place. Today, Houston is one of the most racially diverse cities in the United States, and at the same time it remains one of the most starkly segregated. Ponton’s study demonstrates how and why segregation has become a permanent feature in our cities and offers powerful tools for imagining the world otherwise.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aAfropessimism (Philosophy). 0aBlack peoplexCivil rightszTexaszHoustonxHistory. 0aBlack peoplexCivil rightszUnited StatesxCases. 0aBlack peoplexSegregationzTexaszHoustonxHistoriography. 0aBlack peoplexSegregationzTexaszHoustonxHistory. 0aBlack peoplexSegregationzUnited StatesxCases. 0aBlack peoplezTexaszHoustonxSocial conditionsxHistory. 0aRacism against Black peoplezTexaszHoustonxHistory. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh  aAfropessimism, Africana philosophy, afterlives of slavery, Black Male Studies, black manhood, Black Nihilism, black womanhood, civil rights movement, Frantz Fanon, history and theory, humanism, gender and sexuality, interracial marriage and sex, liberalism, police brutality, Texas, slumming, student movement, race and criminality, Black Studies, Texas Southern University.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Texas Press Complete eBook-Package 2024z978311079783140uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/32847740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781477328484423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781477328484/original  a978-3-11-079783-1  University of Texas Press Complete eBook-Package 2024b2024  aEBA_EMB  aGBV-deGruyter-alles